   This guarantees the clustering persist either fully precedes the wipe or (if it hadn't started by phase 3) is absent, so no anchors are written into a wiped DB in the common case.

Robustness upgrade to fully close the window for large libraries (recommended, since the ~5s wait can expire mid-PHASE-2): introduce a face_cluster_cancel: Arc<AtomicBool> that the clustering closure checks once at the top of PHASE 3, immediately before db.lock() at face_clustering.rs:288 — if set, bail out (return a no-op/cancelled result) without persisting. handle_wipe_library sets that flag before its wait so a clustering run still in PHASE 2 when the wait expires will abort its persist instead of resurrecting phantom persons. Clear the cancel flag after the wipe completes. This makes the interlock deterministic rather than timing-dependent, matching the engine's single-DB-owner self-enforcement principle the existing scan interlock comment (wipe.rs:20-26) invokes.

