Normalize both operands to the same non-verbatim form using the existing crate::util::path_safety::strip_extended_length (which strips `\\?\` / `\\?\UNC\` WITHOUT resolving the symlink — std::fs::canonicalize must NOT be used here because it follows the junction and defeats detection). In has_reparse_point_in_chain:

#[cfg(windows)]
fn has_reparse_point_in_chain(parent: &Path, root: &Path) -> bool {
    use std::os::windows::fs::MetadataExt;
    use crate::util::path_safety::strip_extended_length;
    const FILE_ATTRIBUTE_REPARSE_POINT: u32 = 0x400;
    let root = strip_extended_length(root);
    let mut cur = strip_extended_length(parent);
    loop {
        if let Ok(meta) = std::fs::symlink_metadata(&cur) {
            if (meta.file_attributes() & FILE_ATTRIBUTE_REPARSE_POINT) != 0 {
                return true;
            }
        }
        if cur == root || !cur.starts_with(&root) {
            break;
        }
        if !cur.pop() { break; }
    }
    false
}

I empirically verified this version: it returns true for a junction planted at an intermediate ancestor (root\Photos) and false for a clean tree (no over-rejection). Note: stripping both to plain form works for drive-letter and UNC paths via strip_extended_length's two branches; the comparison stays case-sensitive like the original (acceptable — both come from the same library_root string so casing is consistent). Add a regression test that plants a junction in an INTERMEDIATE ancestor (not the leaf parent) under library_root and asserts the move is rejected (the existing tests only cover ensure_inside_root, never the reparse chain). Do NOT adopt the finding's alternative suggestion of canonicalizing the parent — that resolves the junction and the bug remains.

Replace the dedup block at restructure_semantic.rs lines 186-217 so disambiguation and the uniqueness set both operate on the sanitized folder name:

```rust
let mut pretty = base.clone();
let mut safe = crate::util::path_safety::safe_filename_component(&pretty);
// If the *folder* name is already claimed by another new-group cluster,
// prefer the next distinctive term, then a numeric suffix — checking in the
// sanitized namespace that actually backs the directory (#9, illegal-char
// collision e.g. "16:9" vs "16/9" both -> "16_9").
if used_group_names.contains(&safe) {
    if let Some(extra) = terms.get(2) {
        pretty = format!("{} {}", base, title_case(extra));
        safe = crate::util::path_safety::safe_filename_component(&pretty);
    }
}
let mut n = 2usize;
while used_group_names.contains(&safe) {
    pretty = format!("{} {}", base, n);
    safe = crate::util::path_safety::safe_filename_component(&pretty);
    n += 1;
}
used_group_names.insert(safe.clone());
// ... confidence / reason unchanged, still use `pretty` for the human-facing text ...
(library_root.join(&safe), pretty, confidence, reason)
```

Key points: (1) the HashSet now stores `safe`, the on-disk folder name; (2) every candidate (`base`, `base + terms[2]`, `base n`) is re-sanitized before the membership check, so two clusters that collapse to the same `safe` are forced apart by the numeric suffix; (3) `pretty` is still carried into `category`/`reason` for display, so the UI label and the on-disk folder now stay consistent. Add a regression test: two clusters whose top terms yield `pretty` "16:9" and "16/9" must produce distinct destination parents (e.g. ".../16_9" and ".../16_9 2").
